   132	It is now more than 160 years since Carnot started the science of
   133	thermodynamics with the first statement of what is perhaps the most
   134	fundamental of all principles for predicting macroscopic events. But we
   135	have not yet understood and exploited all its implications.
   136	
   137	At first, progress came rapidly; from Carnot's principle (no heat engine
   138	E can be more efficient than a reversible one R with the same upper
   139	and lower temperatures $t, t^\prime$) it follows that all reversible engines
   140	must have the same efficiency depending only on $t, t^\prime$. So, as Kelvin
   141	saw, the reversible efficiency e(R) must define a universal
   142	temperature scale T(t), independent of the properties of any
   143	particular substance: $$e(R) = 1 - T^\prime/T. \tag{1}$$ From the first law the actual
   144	efficiency is $e = 1 - Q^\prime/Q$; so as Clausius saw, Carnot's inequality
   145	$e \le e(R)$ implies the existence of a new function of the
   146	thermodynamic state $$S = \int dQ/T \tag{2}$$ which he named \"entropy\", with
   147	the property that in a macroscopic change that begins and ends in
   148	thermal equilibrium, the total entropy of all bodies involved cannot
   149	decrease: $$S_{\text{final}} \ge S_{\text{initial}}, \tag{3}$$ *ergo*, if it
   150	increases, the process is irreversible.
   151	
