   180	Turning now to macrophenomena, it is clear that far more than (3) can be
   181	said about how they proceed. We enunciate a rather basic principle,
   182	which might be dismissed as an obvious triviality were it not for the
   183	fact that it is not recognized in any of the literature known to this
   184	writer:
   185	> *If any macrophenomenon is found to be reproducible, then it follows
   186	> that all microscopic details that were not reproduced, must be
   187	> irrelevant for understanding and predicting it. In particular, all
   188	> circumstances that were not under the experimenter's control are very
   189	> likely not to be reproduced, and therefore are very likely not to be
   190	> relevant.*
   191	Now in the laboratory we find that irreversible processes follow a
   192	definite course; control of a few initial macroscopic quantities is
   193	sufficient to yield a reproducible result. We observe this not only
   194	close to equilibrium as in heat conduction and viscous laminar flow, but
   195	also far from equilibrium as in shock waves, fast chemical reactions,
   196	and lasers.
   197	*Ergo*, information about those initial macroscopic values, together
   198	with suitable general prior information I whose nature we have not yet
   199	specified, must be sufficient for theoretical prediction of the result.
